h2. Task

Enable default server-side encryption on all S3 buckets storing customer data.

h2. Steps

# *AWS Console* → S3 → Select bucket → Properties → Default encryption
# Enable *SSE-S3 (AES-256)* or *SSE-KMS* on each bucket
# Repeat for all environments:

   - {{eg-pz-dev-s3-branding-ohio}}

   - {{eg-pz-qa}}

   - {{eg-pz-stage}}

   - {{eg-pz-prod}}

   - {{eg-pz-bces-prod}}

   - Any reporting/photo storage buckets

h2. Notes

* *Zero code changes required* — AWS handles encryption/decryption transparently
* Automatically encrypts all *existing and future* objects at rest
* No impact on application performance or API calls
* SOC2 Control: _"Customer data must be encrypted at rest using AES-256"_

h2. Verification

* After enabling, upload a test file → check S3 object properties → confirm encryption shows {{SSE-S3}} or {{SSE-KMS}}

h2. Summary

The {{GET /sld/v2/<sld_id>}} API currently returns {{ir_sessions}} as a list of session objects, but each session object does not include {{equipment_ids}}. We need to add {{equipment_ids}} to each session object in the {{ir_sessions}} response array.

h2. Current Behavior

The {{ir_sessions}} list in the {{/sld/v2/}} GET response returns session objects with fields like id, name, description, photo_type, dates, priority, etc. *No `equipment_ids` field is present.*

h2. Expected Behavior

Each object in the {{ir_sessions}} list should include an {{equipment_ids}} field - an array of equipment IDs associated with that session.

{noformat}{
  "ir_sessions": [
    {
      "id": "...",
      "name": "...",
      "equipment_ids": ["eq-uuid-1", "eq-uuid-2"],
      ...
    }
  ]
}{noformat}

h2. Technical Details

* *Route:* {{app/routes/sld_routes.py}}
* *Controller:* {{app/controllers/sld_controller.py}} - {{SLDController.get_sld_full_v2()}}
* *Session Model:* {{app/models/Session.py}} - {{Session.to_dict()}} method
* *Equipment Model:* {{app/models/TestEquipment.py}}

h2. Acceptance Criteria

* Each session object in the {{ir_sessions}} array includes an {{equipment_ids}} field
* {{equipment_ids}} is an array of UUID strings representing associated equipment
* Existing API response structure is not broken
* API performance is not significantly impacted (use efficient queries/joins)

As a platform admin, I need the onboarding API to assign the correct alliance partner and seed all required master data records so that a new customer tenant is immediately functional after onboarding.

Per the [Customer Onboarding Technical Guide|https://egalvanic.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/Product/pages/53837825/Customer+Onboarding+Technical+Guide] (Sections 4.5 and 7), each new company must be linked to an alliance partner and populated with default master records.

h4. Alliance Partner Assignment
* Accept alliance partner selection: {{eGalvanic}} or {{BCES-IQ}}
* Update {{companies.alliance_partner_id}} to reference the correct {{alliance_partners.id}}
* Alliance partner determines target database and branding defaults

h4. Master Data Seeding
On company creation, auto-populate the following master tables with default records scoped to the new company:
* {{forms}}
* {{form_instances}}
* {{node_classes}}
* {{edge_classes}}
* {{issue_classes}}
* {{node_subtypes}}
* {{procedures}}
* {{shortcuts}}
* {{mapping_procedure_shortcut}}

Default records must be sourced from a maintained seed template (not hardcoded). Seeding must be idempotent: re-running for the same company does not create duplicates.

h4. Transaction Safety
* Alliance partner assignment and master data seeding must execute within a single database transaction
* If any seeding step fails, the entire operation rolls back

{color:#de350b}⚠️ _Cross-System Impact:_{color} Master data must be seeded into the correct database (eGalvanic or BCES-IQ) based on alliance partner. Ensure {{partner_db_middleware.py}} routes to the correct database connection.

h4. Cross-System Checklist
* [ ] Changes tested on DEV
* [ ] Changes tested on QA
* [ ] BCES-IQ migration planned (if DB change)
* [ ] Environment variables added to all locations (if new env var)
* [ ] Verified both PROD environments after deployment

📄 Reference: [Cross-System Validation Guide|https://egalvanic.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/ENGR/pages/102826000]

h4. Acceptance Criteria
* Alliance partner is correctly assigned based on admin selection and stored in {{companies.alliance_partner_id}}
* All 9 master data tables are populated with default records scoped to the new company
* Master data seed templates are externalized (JSON or database-backed), not hardcoded
* Seeding is idempotent: calling the endpoint twice for the same company produces no duplicate records
* If any master table seeding fails, the entire transaction rolls back including the alliance partner assignment
* Master data is written to the correct database as determined by alliance partner via {{partner_db_middleware.py}}
* Changes verified on BCES-IQ environment

h3. User Story

* As a developer, when I need common functionality like hierarchy building, I want reusable utilities so that I don't duplicate code.
* As a maintainer, when I fix a bug in common logic, I want it fixed everywhere so that inconsistencies don't occur.

h3. Context

Common code patterns (node hierarchy building, task completion calculation, search/filter logic) are duplicated across multiple ViewModels. This creates maintenance burden and potential for bugs when logic diverges.

h3. Scope

Create shared utilities for:

* Node hierarchy building
* Task completion calculation
* Search/filter logic

h3. Acceptance Criteria

* ✅ Shared utilities created for node hierarchy building, task completion calculation, search/filter logic
* ✅ ViewModels refactored to use shared utilities
* ✅ Code duplication reduced across ViewModels
* ✅ Unit tests added for utility functions

h3. Technical Implementation

{code:swift}// Create utility classes/extensions
struct NodeHierarchyBuilder {
    static func buildHierarchy(from nodes: [Node]) -> [Building] {
        // Centralized hierarchy building logic
    }
}

struct TaskCalculator {
    static func calculateCompletionPercentage(for tasks: [Task]) -> Double {
        // Optimized O(n) calculation
    }
}

extension Array where Element == Task {
    func filtered(by searchText: String) -> [Task] {
        // Reusable filter logic
    }
}{code}

h3. Related Issue

* Relates to ZP-897 (iOS Architecture Refactor)

